div.div:
The impurities that are always present in alkaline electrolytes in the form of trace amounts of transition metals have been reported to affect experimental results on electrolysis performances due to the incorporation of Fe into Ni-based electrocatalysts, indicating that the increase in electrocatalytic activity is attributed to the adsorption of Fe impurities. However, in case of the electrocatalytic water splitting using a catalyst which already contains enough Fe atoms, it is confirmed that purification of the alkaline electrolyte, which requires high cost and complicated process, did not significantly affect the catalytic performance during OER at a current density of 100 mA cm

 –2

for 100 h (

 Figure S8

). These results show that bimetallic catalysts containing Fe atoms are less susceptible to Fe impurities in the electrolyte.

